 style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Throughout this debate, concerns raised have focussed very much on soft tissue injuries caused by whiplash to the neck, shoulders and back so we would expect the Government to focus on this type of injury when developing its register. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Certainly, widening the scope of the register too soon, without a tried and tested process, could be counter-productive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: it would take significantly longer to introduce, as a larger body of medical experts would require accreditation against a range of spe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cialisations.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If the Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">does </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">decide to restrict the accredited register of experts to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">injuries caused by whiplash to the neck, shoulders and back</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, we suggest the expert should be allowed to refer patients to other non-accredited medical specialists</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as required.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Whatever direction is taken, however, the approach must be absolutely clear.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If the objective of combatting fraud and exaggeration </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to be achieved, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he emphasis in developing this system must be on quality rather than on creating the chea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pest option. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eople </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with genuine injuries </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">must </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">undergo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">consistent and high </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">quality</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> examination</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and receive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">medical reports which help them to recover from their injuries, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which help them to obtain the right amount of compensation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Excellen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ce in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">quality</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> reporting would make fraud and exaggeration more easily identifiable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The Government should guard against any standardised process which puts speed and uniformity above the individual needs of patients. It </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">must</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be remembered that whiplash-relate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d injuries can be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">very serious: independent research commissioned by APIL last year</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> established that 20 per cent of people with whiplash-related injuries were still suffering from symptoms over a year </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">after the incident</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.  The Government favours a stan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dard medical report form for use in all claims, but</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">this will inevitably mean that reporting doctors would have to confine their  remarks to a standard template or a drop-box option which will limit the amount of     information provided.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">7.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Lack of det</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ail will not advance the Government’s objective of address</span><span sty