 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">10.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is unfortunate that this sentiment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">was conditional on other developments, but still represents welcome progress, particularly when some in the industry have expressed their disquiet publicly about the practice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">11. I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is clear that t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">his practice should be banned by means of legislation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">here </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, however,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> rule changes which c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">introduced</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">quickly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> help to change behaviour in relation to this practice and we are, at the time of writing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in dialogue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with the Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on necessary changes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">12. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> medical report should not be required at the very beginning of the claim process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> requirement to produce a medical report at the outset would generate unnecessary costs and delays in claims which do not proceed.   </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">13. O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> an improved system of med</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ical reporting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has been</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> developed, it must be used. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While the practice of pre-medical offers persists in whiplash cases, fraud can continue undetected. To stop fraud, pre-medical offers must be banned, and the quality of medical reporting must be higher –</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the two will work in tandem.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">14. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Third party capture is another route by which fraud can take place undetected. Insurers should also commit to obtaining medical evidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> if</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> dealing with people direct.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Injured people must be protected from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">abuses whic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h do take place when insurers deal with the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> direct, including </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the exertion of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">undue influence and inequality of information and bargaining power.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">     </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Fraud d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ata </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">15. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">laimant lawyers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be gatekeepers against people who try to make fraudulent claims if relevant information held by the insurance industry </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> made available to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">them</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Claimant solicitors could be of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">real </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">value in the fight against fraud if they  have access to the number and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">type of accidents </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a potential client has been involved, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">information about </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">personal injury claims arising from them.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This information is currently held by insurers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and there is no logical disadvantage to it being made available to claimant soli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">citor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The date any previous injur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y was</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sustained would also be very helpful as, if the case is genuine, this information could assist medical professionals to provide the best treatment for patient</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are greatly encouraged</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to learn </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that discussions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> about </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">this are ongoing in the insurance industry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and that information may become available in due course</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Ideally, this data would need to be available at the time of implementation of the new medical reporting system.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Small Claims Court Limit</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">16. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The announcement that there would be no change to the small claims court limit at this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">time</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> was very much welcomed by AP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IL. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he small claims court was not designed for people who represent themselves in personal injury cases; raising the limit would have h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ad no impact on fraud whatsoever, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and this was, after all, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">key</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">purpose </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of the Government’s consultation; it would have had an enormous </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and negative </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">impact on the courts, which would have been overwhelmed by litigants in person who would have struggled to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> understand the court system; and it would have led to another explosion of spam calls and texts from claims management companies who would have exploited the situation of people who would no longer be able to afford legal representation.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n increase</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e limit would</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, therefore,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">en</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> wholly counterproductive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">17. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is to be hoped that proposals can now be developed which will assist all concerned in ensuring fair compensation for those </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">injured people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, while working to eradicate fraudulent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and exa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">erated claims.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:18pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#002d62; font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:18pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#002d62; font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11.5pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Myriad Pro'; font-size:12pt">Page </span><span style="font-family:'Myriad Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font-family:'Myriad Pro'; font-size:12pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:'Myriad Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The Whiplash Report 2012, page 12, available here: </span><a href="http://files.apil.org.uk/campaigns/the-whiplash-report-2012.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://files.apil.org.uk/campaigns/the-whiplash-report-2012.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Speech by Rob Cummings to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Manchester</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Law Society Autumn Personal Injury Conference, 11 November 2013</span></p></body></html>